segments.text: November 17th, 1989, Matt Spahn is interviewing me for a journalism project.
How did that go?
This is an interview with Judith A. Baer by Matt W. Spahn.
on November 17, 1989, at Bolton Hall, Texas A&M University, concerning feminism.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge, I am asking you to donate this tape to me or to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
Is that all right with you?
Right.
Let's begin.
Tell me about yourself.
Okay.
I was born in Mount Kisco, New York, while my father was at Wright Field in Dayton, Ohio, during World War II, and my mother was visiting her family.
When the war ended, we moved to Cambridge, Massachusetts, where my father got a PhD at Harvard.
I like to describe myself as a second-generation political scientist.
We lived in Cambridge until I was 14, then we moved to Arlington, which is near Cambridge, where I went to high school.
I then went to Bryn Mawr College, got an AB there in 1968, got my MA from the University of Chicago in Political Science in 71, and my PhD in 1974.
And after a long series of cross-country moves, trials and tribulations, I am an associate professor of political science at Texas A&M.
Thank you.
Let's start off your early childhood because we want to see how this has led up to you.

There is a profile of the professional woman which has her as either the oldest child of daughters only or the only child of someone who is very close to and influenced by her father and grows up in a non-traditional family.
That is not me.
I am the oldest, and I have three younger brothers, no sisters, and we grew up in a family which was extremely traditional with respect to sex roles.
And I have always said to people that I've been a feminist ever since I can remember.
When I was eight years old, I decided I wanted to be the first woman president.
You've got to remember this is back in the 1950s.
The 1950s were not a great decade for feminism.
He was high school, and by that time it was the 1960s.
I remember high school as the worst four years of my life so far anyway.
And things only got better when I went to college.
I went to college planning to become a lawyer, maybe possibly the first woman Supreme Court Justice, which it's already too late for.
And in my junior year, I met a great teacher, Peter Bachrach at Bryn Mawr College, and it was partly his influence.
that made me want to go into graduate school in political science.
And then I went to the University of Chicago.
And about that time, and this is the late 1960s, the feminist movement, the newer wave of the feminist movement came along.
And I just wish it had happened 20 years earlier, but I really believe that if I'd been born in the 1920s or 30s instead of the 1940s, I would have gone absolutely crazy.
So it was very fortunate the feminist movement came along when it did.
You said the new wave in the late 60s.
When was the very first wave?
The very first feminist movement in this country is usually seen as having begun in 1848 with the convention at Seneca Falls, New York.
Well, there had been, okay, the first American woman to write about feminism was Judith Sergeant Murray, and her book on the equality of the sexes was published in 1790.
It wasn't very influential at the time.
She was influenced by the great British 18th century feminist Mary Wollstonecraft.
The women who convened at Seneca Falls, and prominent among them were Susan B. Anthony and Elizabeth Cady Stanton, Lucretia Mott.
Most of them came out of the abolitionist movement, the movement to abolish slavery.
There had been, in the earlier 1840s, a large anti-slavery convention in London.
And Stanton and Mott, who were present, were not allowed to speak because it was considered unseemly for women to speak in public, and they decided it wasn't only the slaves that needed liberating.
There's a real parallel with the later feminist movement because most of us had been involved in the civil rights movement and also in the student and anti-war movement of the 60s.
But there's a Seneca Falls Declaration, and it's modeled after the Declaration of Independence, where they talk about histories of injuries and usurpations.
And they mention such things as the practice then of giving custody of children to the father in divorce, the practice of coverture, which meant that when a man and woman were married,
The notion was the couple was one, and that one was the husband.
The woman could not sign contracts.
She could not own property.
She had no separate identity.
And, of course, the denial of the vote.

Getting the laws of the different states amended so that women could vote and getting a national constitutional amendment was the goal of the first feminist movement and that of course culminated in 1920 with the passage of the 19th amendment.
And after that, the movement kind of fizzled out because that had been the goal.
All the energies had gone toward that goal.
The earliest generation of feminists, Anthony and Stanton, were dead by now.
And there just was really not that much energy.
Now, yeah, go ahead.
You talked about the movement in the late 60s and how it was part of the student movement, the anti-war movement.
What peoples did that movement share with the other movements?
Was there a completely different group?
Was there some overlaying?
No, there was a considerable amount of overlap.
Jo Freeman, who's published quite a bit, who's the name she published under in the late 60s, was Joreen.
We were graduate students together at the University of Chicago, and she was...
a veteran of that movement.
People like Casey Hayden, Tom Hayden's first wife.
But there were others who, well, like me, I was never prominent in the civil rights movement.
I marched and I carried banners and I licked stamps and I put posters up all over town.
Carnation can milk, by the way, is very good if you want to make posters stick to trees.
Most people don't know that, even though it's messy.

And I was really, because I really concentrated on school when I was in college, and I was much too shy to take a prominent role, and I'm not one of the world's best-known feminists either, but I'm a little more prominent in that movement.
And one of the things that happened that got the feminist movement going
was the publication in 1963 of The Feminine Mystique by Betty Friedan.
And Betty Friedan was a woman who had gone to graduate school in the 1940s, dropped out to be a housewife, married, had three kids, and then really became a journalist and looked around for projects.
And the 1960s, well, that was still the time when Leave It, I don't know if you've ever seen Leave It to Beaver, you know, all those comedies, Father Knows Best.
That was the model, the very patriarchal family.

and you were not that everybody lived that way but you were expected to and all of a sudden for dan was saying hey being a housewife is not right for every woman it's a it's a good idea to be a lawyer to have careers to go to graduate school we have really narrowed the
possibilities for women.
And of course, she was widely thought of as being absolutely crazy.
And abuse was just heaped on her.
And when I read this book, I was a freshman in college.
And in fact, it was the book I took along on our geology field trip.
geology was a science requirement, which I took very reluctantly.
And I'm sitting there reading this in the hotel room, nodding and thinking, oh God, where has this been?
I'm not alone.
I'm not crazy.
And a lot of us felt that way.
I think that you can never really date the beginning of a movement with any precision.
I think if you dated this one, it would be in the spring of 1968 at Columbia University.
You may have heard of the student uprising and the trying to prevent and successfully preventing the building of a gym in Harlem.
which the people who lived there couldn't use, and many of whom were losing their homes because of it.
And at that time, during the sit-in, there was a notice that was put up to all women, you are in a liberated area, you don't have to do the cleaning and cooking anymore.
And then in the fall of 68, I began graduate school.
The Women's Caucus in our department, Political Science, and in many others, was organized in the next few months.
And all of a sudden, between 68 and 69, there was a women's movement everywhere.
And it wasn't really well-perceived in the mass media or anything like that.
the things that happened.
The ERA was brought up in the Congress in 1970.
It failed then.
Then it was brought up in 72.
And for a while, it looked as though it was going to pass.
Title IX of the Civil Rights Act of 1972 gave women equal educational opportunities.
And it's just been amazing.
There are now 40% of the law students in this country are women.
In medicine, the figures are the same.
They approach 50%.
The same is true in academia and graduate programs.
The changes have just been overwhelming since that time.
Has the feminist movement gone to other nations?
Absolutely.
There is a feminist movement just about everywhere in the world, even in places you wouldn't expect, like Spain and India.
One of the exceptions

Our near exceptions is Scandinavia, and I remember reading one article and saying, hey, how come in Scandinavia, where the women are probably most advanced, there's no feminist movement, as if to suggest that a feminist movement is really superfluous.
Well, my feeling is that there's very comparatively little feminism in Scandinavia because they don't need it.
as yet.
There is equal opportunity.
In fact, I was at a conference in Sweden this summer, and a Swedish sociologist spoke, and she said, well, the joke is that the state is a woman's best friend.
With the state, you don't need a man, because you can have your career, have your children,
A lot of people in Scandinavia are unwed mothers.
And I don't mean 16-year-olds living in poverty.
That doesn't happen.
I mean 35-year-old women college professors.
And because you get all these benefits and you do have equal opportunity, there is probably... You have the same kind of problem in Sweden that you have here.
Men do not share housework equally or childcare.
But things are very, very different.
The goals tend to be different because there are many countries in which
Things are less advanced.
I mean, in India, one of the goals is the abolition of sati, the custom that when a man dies, his widow jumps on his funeral pyre.
This is illegal in India, but it still goes on.
And for many women, the choice is between sati and destitution as a widow.
Widows are very, very poor.
in India.

And another thing that often happens is selective abortion, because a fetus is female, which for a woman in Asia may be a viable choice, because if she has a girl, her husband and her in-laws are going to blame her and make her life miserable.
But it would be nice to have that change.
But yes, there's feminism everywhere.
Let's talk about the feminist movement in the 70s.
What happened then?
or its goals for that decade?

Well, equal educational opportunities, which we're very close to, affordable child care, which we're not, the ERA, which of course was defeated, significant changes in the laws having to do with rape and sexual abuse.
That has come about.
There was very much a counter-trend, and this was not the fault of feminists, although people often blame them, such a thing as no-fault divorce, which was a reform primarily sponsored by...

male legislators and lawyers, which was a very good idea, to remove the notion that one person got a divorce from another who was mistreating him or her and had to pay lots of alimony, that divorce was seen as something that happened when a marriage ended.
But the problem was that this has meant increasingly
that divorced women, if they have children and they have backtracked their career ambitions to take care of their kids in their home, often end up in poverty.
But it's been a way for men to get out of obligations to their families, and that's certainly something that has to change.
What did you do in the 70s?
I got a PhD.
I began my publication career.
with a book and an article, the book, The Chains of Protection, the article on sexual equality in the Burger Court in 1978.
I joined now.
myself concentrating on being a scholar, and I did.
Scholarship took a front seat, and feminist activism took a back seat, although I did go to the march supporting the extension of the deadline for the ERA in 1978.
Let's talk about your book, The Chains of Protection.
Can you give me a synopsis of that?
Yeah.
That was my dissertation, and there's one more chapter that I wrote for Greenwood Press.
Basically, I was looking at the court decisions pertaining to special labor legislation for women, what is called protective labor legislation.
And this was an old idea to...
to pass laws saying that you couldn't make women work more than a certain number of hours a day or make them work at night or lift a lot of weights and so on.
And in many ways I wish I were writing that book now because
There was an old controversy in the early feminist movement which is arising again now.
And essentially what happened in the 1800s when it became more and more common for women to work outside the home, you had the same kind of sex-segregated labour market.
as we do now.
There were men's jobs and women's jobs, and the women's jobs paid less, and they had to work longer hours, and there was less effort given to forming unions.
So women couldn't gain concessions through collective bargaining, as men did.

And when legislators began approaching this problem, they saw it not as a problem of women have to work harder, but a problem of women can't work as hard, they're weaker, they bear children, they have special needs, and so on.
And that was essentially the basis on which protective labor legislation was upheld.

Now there was a whole group of feminists, people who supported women's suffrage, people like Jane Addams of Hull House, probably the most famous, but also Josephine Goldmark, who wrote some of the early court briefs, Florence Kelly, and so on, who supported this legislation because they essentially accepted the family with the traditional female role as a given.
Women needed concessions because their mission in life was to be wives and mothers.
Feminists like Anthony and Stanton disagreed and felt, well, the role in the family might be oppressive.
We need full equality.
It means moving into the professions, having the choice not to bear children, and so on.
And while the advocates of protective labor legislation supported women's suffrage, the advocates of women's suffrage did not always support protective labor legislation.
After the 19th Amendment was ratified, then you had a real split.
The social feminists who became active in the labor movement still supporting the special laws.
The National Women's Party, under the leadership of people like Alice Pohl, disagreeing with them, and there were lots of charges made.

Proponents of protective labor legislation said that the others were anti-family, and people like Alice Paul said that the social feminists, as they were called, were really hurting women by endorsing their traditional role.
You can guess, which I'll bet without any problem, what side the mainstream media, the political parties were on.
They were on the side of the social feminists.
We've got the same split now.
Maybe you remember the controversy last spring over the mommy track.
The proposal by a woman who really should know better, who is an expert in
women's working patterns.
That in the professions, you have two tracks.
If the woman wants to work full time, which means 80 hours a week in business and law, she can concentrate on that.
If the woman wants to work part time, which means 40 hours, which most of us think of as full time, and raise children, then she could be on the quote unquote mommy track.
And she will really abandon all hope of really reaching the top echelons.
And a lot of people think that's a very good idea.
I think one woman who would is Sylvia Ann Hewlett.

Three years ago, she wrote a book which became very controversial called A Lesser Life, and she attacked the feminist movement represented by people like Ferdinand, now Gloria Steinem, and so on, for not understanding that the central fact of most women's lives was their home and their children.
Well of course, even if that were true for everyone, that's only true for about 20 years.
And she felt that what women needed was maternity leaves, child care, concessions so they could be in the home, and possibly even a salary for housework.
That's an extremely controversial proposal, which she did not make.
And she would probably support the mommy track.
But there are also a group of feminists, and I put myself firmly in this category,
group who suggests that we need to take a look at the family itself, because as presently constituted, it is oppressive of women.
There are a sociologist named Arlie Hochschild has just published a book called The Second Shift, and she looks at working women.
but blue-collar women and professionals and sees, you know, now we've got the two-career marriage, great.
The man has one full-time job, then he comes home and relaxes.
The woman has one full-time job at work, she comes home and has another
full-time job of taking care of the kids in the house, and things are not shared.
And the mommy track proposal is just really buying into that.
Now, some women, I think you would be one of them, say, well, women want it that way.
They want to be the primary caregivers.
I don't think so.
I doubt that any woman wants to come home and start taking care of her kids while her husband sits in front of the TV and drinks a beer.
I just do not believe that.
Now, it's certainly true that women bear the children.
Okay, for nine months they've got exclusive responsibility.
After that, when they're breastfeeding,
they've got a responsibility that the man can't share.
But when you've got somebody whose two kids are seven and five, I mean, nobody's nursing their five-year-olds.
And you've got a pattern where she comes home and starts working, he comes home and collapses.
Come on.
Nobody's going to tell me that that's just.
Right.
That sounds analogous to the...
biological need for a woman to nurture, that big argument.
The biological fuck.
I love it.
Oh, I love it.
It was something that was...
invented, I mean, the term was invented by some physician, I think, male.

You know, that when you get into your late 30s and early 40s, you hear your biological clock ticking, and you get frantic if you haven't had a baby yet, and I am here to tell you that that does not apply to everyone.
Of course, you know, to some extent, we all have needs we are told that we have.

But it's funny, I was reading a novel recently, a piece of trash, and it has to do with a woman who was in medical school in the late 1950s, and she's talking about, I hear my biological clock ticking, well, the term didn't exist in the 50s.
I mean, the writer who is writing in 1988 is applying it to this woman.
It's as if you wrote a novel...
about the Civil War, and you had people saying like and you know and groovy and other slang from the 1960s.
It's just anachronistic.
It's very stupid.
But, you know, I think now, looking back on the book,
Of course, with hindsight, knowing that the issue I was talking about is now so very, very important, I would have polarized the book more.
I know that I was criticized.
A couple of the reviewers said, well, she's too strident.
She's too feminist.
She's too prejudiced.
And now I think I would not be more moderate.
I would really be stronger, be more feminist, be more polarized in writing that book.
Since this is 1989, we can look back on this past decade and try to get some perspective on it.
What happened in the 80s for the movement?
Oh, boy.
The feminist movement ran into a big problem, and that was known as the Reagan administration.
And the ERA was defeated, which a lot of people attributed to extremism, stridency, and all of those things.
And I think that we made a big mistake, but I think the big mistake that we made was not understanding that state legislatures are different from Congress.
Congress is not a microcosm of... No, I'm going to put it another way.
The 50 state legislatures are not a microcosm of Congress.
Different people get elected there.
The patterns are very different.
And I think that in many ways, the movement in the 80s was not...
Well, often it's been said that the feminist movement is dead because it was all these horrible man-haters.
And essentially, I think that we were not appropriately willing to condemn certain patterns of male behavior.
One of the things that you saw in the 1980s was the divorce revolution.
More and more, he and she get married, he has a career, she either stays home or held back on her career to raise the kids.
Fifteen years later, they get a divorce.
There's one study in California that showed that after a divorce, a man's income rises, the woman keeps the kids, the family income rises.
And one sociologist described divorced women with children as the new poor.
The 80s was also the decade that saw the feminization of poverty.
More and more the people who were poor were women raising children.
Okay, one of the things that I should have mentioned and that I didn't was that one of the goals of the feminist movement and of the great majority of the people who label themselves feminists
is reproductive freedom, and that includes the right to an abortion.
And of course there has been, if you look from Rovers' way to web services in the reproductive health services this summer, there was a significant back step in that.
Now the news from the latest elections are very good.
There seems to be a pendulum swinging in favor of Joyce.
Let's talk a little bit about the court.
I don't mean to limit you and say that's your specialty, the Constitution of the Supreme Court, but I know you're an expert on that subject.
Did you talk about that in the 80s, what the court did?
Yes.
Okay.
Ronald Reagan ran for president twice.

promising that he would put justices on the court, who would overturn Roe versus Wade, who would backtrack on affirmative action, who would do a few other things like restore credit schools, which don't have to do with women, but are also similarly conservative.
Very few people believed him.
The vast majorities who voted for him in 80 and 84 didn't take him seriously.
He meant it.
They were wrong not to do so.
The real irony
is that Reagan's economic policies, which were popular for a lot of voters, aren't going to come to fruition, and his jurisprudence may.
I mean, these guys, Kennedy, Rehnquist now as chief, Scalia, want to overturn Roe v. Wade.
They are slashing affirmative action.
The only wild card was O'Connor, and she came up in the first term when the...
real stringency with interviewing potential Supreme Court nominees had not been instituted by Edwin Leese and his Justice Department.
By the way, it's not only the Supreme Court, it's the whole federal judiciary.
Almost half of the people who are now federal judges have been appointed by Reagan.
And I think
Now, he clearly has got the majority that is going to kill affirmative action and has, essentially.
He is one vote short of the majority on Roe.
Now this may all become moot.
The Illinois case, which is scheduled for this term, the one that puts heavy restrictions on clinics, may not be heard at all.
Because the attorney general who brought the case is running for governor and he cannot get money because of his anti-choice stance.
And now he's trying to get a compromise in the case and get it withdrawn from the court.
So it's going to be interesting to see what Bush is going to do.
Bush is in real trouble on this whole issue.
And Bush promised that he was going to appoint judges who would overturn Roe and do all these things.
It's going to be interesting to notice, if you will.
You were talking about Reagan and how he has so many people put on the bench.
What could that do to the movement?
I think it has already done a great deal and what it has told us is that don't go to the Supreme Court.
The situation is not analogous to the blacks in the 1950s to Brown v. Board of Education.
And more and more cases have been filed in state courts, which are sometimes receptive.
People have gone to the legislatures and to Congress.
One of the things that I think could happen, I think that pro-choice has the potential of bringing about a significant realignment in American politics.
I think this is very good news for the Democrats.
Now, I don't think the Democrats have the guts
to run on the pro-choice issue and make it theirs.
And I don't think the Republicans have the stupidity to let them.
And right now, as I said, if you saw that article in the Eagle over the weekend, I think the identification is with the Democrats.
I don't think it's going to stay that way.
So there will not be a realignment.
But I think basically that's a failure of nerve on the part of the Democratic Party.
I've voted Democrat all my life, and I probably always will, but I'm really pretty sick of their cowardice at the national level at the moment.
Let's talk about your other book, 1983, Equality Under the Constitution.
This was the book where I tried to go from feminism to a general theory of equality.
I'll tell you what I do not mean.
There was a cliche that was very common in the late 60s and early 70s.
You heard this from Menelak.
Let's not talk about women's liberation.
Let's not talk about human liberation.
And what that meant basically is let's not talk about the way I oppress you.
Let's talk about the way other society oppresses me.
And that isn't what I meant.
But I wanted to ask, if you are a feminist, if you are committed to sexual equality, what does that mean in terms of thinking about society and equality in general?
Well, one of the things that it seemed to me to mean was that if you really believe that women and men are equal, you're saying that...
physical differences really shouldn't be used as a basis for inequality.
And you're also saying that sex roles and, of course, sex itself, sexual activity, should not be used as such a basis.
Isn't that really affected the way...
There are two chapters in the more recent book, one on disability, one on homosexuality.
And those are things that I had to think about a lot as a feminist because it does seem to me that you...
A true commitment to sexual inequality implies looking at sex roles, at sexual orientation, and at physical differences in a new way.
And you know, I went back, there's a chapter in there on the history of the 14th Amendment where I try to look at the whole thing in a new way.
Historical treatments of the 14th Amendment were very big at the time that I was writing.

And in fact, there's a new book out, which I just read a long review of, for a journal, where somebody looks at a lot of us who are writing from, say, the years from 77 and 85, and I'm one of the people he mentions.
I'm at one extreme, and there are a few others at the conservative extreme.
And it was quite interesting.
I had gotten what I expected, some extremely negative reviews from the conservative wing of the political science profession.
I've also got some very positive feedback, although I used to joke for a while that everyone who liked the book wrote me a letter.
Everyone who didn't like the book wrote a review and got it published.
Okay, you wrote in 1985 on feminism and ethics.
Yes.
I was asked to write an introductory article for an issue of a journal called
Women in Politics, and that journal itself owes its existence to the feminist movement.
It began publication in 1980.
And I was basically saying, here are the articles we're publishing on this issue, write what you please.
And one of those articles
by a historian named Robert Booth Fowler had to do with feminism in a place you wouldn't necessarily expect to find feminism, and that is the evangelical Christian movement.
And of course, this is all kinds of ethical issues.
that arise here.

And then another article written by a very good friend of mine, Leslie Goldstein, who teaches political science at the University of Delaware, had to do with the issue of Medicaid funding for abortions and where we should stop and all of this.
She looked at the
All of the biological data on the fetus, you know, when can we say it becomes human and all of that, and found that, you know, for one thing, life doesn't begin.
Life is passed on from the sperm in the ovum.
And that it's really not true that at the moment that these unite, you have a human being.
At the moment that these unite, you have some tissue which has about a 50% chance of being miscarried.
or you wouldn't even call it that, as almost being a kind of tumor which exists in the uterus for a week or two and then leaves.
The whole process of fertilization, implantation, and becoming a pregnancy is a very, very complex process.
And she talked about the ethics of late abortion and all of that.
And I decided to write on feminism

and ethics and what the question is also something that interests me having been brought up as an episcopalian having gone to church to sunday school i'm now unitarian and having been interested in religious questions and ethical questions all my life how does a feminist live a moral life given a commitment to sexual equality what does this mean
And one of the things that has always struck me and has struck most people is that women, in a sense,
bear moral responsibility.
If you go to the supermarket, you see all these magazines directed at women and giving guidance how to run your family, your house.
There is no such thing as men's family circle.
There are no magazines on fathering.
There's lots of magazines for mothers.
If you look at Parents Magazine, look at its advertising, it's very clear who they expect to buy and read against mothers.
And you go to, you know, you look at self-help books in the library.
They're usually addressed to women.
Who goes to church or to temple or listens to sermons?
Women.
And that it's, women are the targets of moral exhortations.
Men are not.
And in a way, there is certainly an imbalance.
Women are the ones who are made to feel guilty about their parents, about their children, about everything else.
Men are not.
But on the other hand, do we want...
to say that it's okay for women to act like men.
And I argue that no, I mean, you don't want, just because men walk out on their families, it doesn't mean that women can.
Just because men do not have the burden of doing things for people, visiting the sick, helping the poor, taking care of your ill mother, your children, your neighbors, that's necessary.
Just because men don't do that
does not really mean that I think that women should give it up too.
There, I think, has to be a balance between excessive responsibility and some sort of moral responsibility.
And I talk a lot about
evangelical Christianity in that article because of course that's very central.
What are your duties as a human being in Christianity?

And how, you know, I point out that the women who are feminists within evangelical Christianity reject all the patriarchal notions, but on the other hand, they wouldn't be comfortable with the message that you get from
what we used to call the human potential movement in the 60s.
Maybe you've seen the poster that says, I do my thing, you do your thing.
Okay, you wouldn't be comfortable with that.

You also wouldn't be comfortable with the go-for-it-baby-and-grab-it school of thought self-help books, which are often written for women in business, that this is something which to a serious Christian
even a feminist or to anyone with serious ethical principles is just not acceptable.
Let's get back to the religious issue again.
There's an idea of thinking of God as mother.
How do you feel about that?
I like it because the ways we think of God are culturally determined.
It makes at least as much sense to think of God as mother as God as father.

I mean, Judeo-Christian tradition is patriarchal, so naturally we see it as God the Father, and of course in Christianity it's Father, Son, and Holy Ghost, and that really kind of lets you out if you're a woman.
But you know, there are some religions
The Eastern religions do not really conceive of God as a figure of such a sort at all.
And of course, these have influenced the Eastern version of Christianity.
For example, in Japanese, the Lord's Prayer is not.
our Father, it is our God who art in heaven because in Japanese culture it simply makes no sense to conceive of God as a Father and women in various religions are
bringing up new patterns.
And I know the Unitarian Church has a curriculum that we're running there now, which is called Cakes for the Queen of Heaven.
And that's from a quotation from Jeremiah, and it's a very nasty quotation, saying, you know, the women like the pagan religions.
instead of Judaism, which of course for him was the truth.
